CB09001 Lin Jianga(cid:1) , Jingxi Xianga(cid:1) Yanwen Duana,b,c and Yong Huanga,c aXiangya International Academy of Translational Medicine at Central South University, Changsha, Hunan, China; bHunan Engineering Research Center of Combinatorial Biosynthesis and Natural Product Drug Discovery, Changsha, Hunan, China; cNational Engineering Research Center of Combinatorial Biosynthesis for Drug Discovery, Changsha, Hunan, China

Xanthone natural products are mainly isolated from plants, lichen and fungi (Vieira and Kijjoa 2005; El-Seedi et al. 2010; Wezeman et al. 2015; Rattanaburi et al. 2020; Yang et al. 2020). Many of them exhibit promising biological activities and serve as drug leads against cancer or drug-resistant pathogens. Xanthones are regarded as privileged structures, since they may alkylate DNAs or interact with various protein tar- including transferrin receptors, protein kinases, a-glycosidases and DNA gets, CONTACT Yanwen Duan (cid:1) (cid:1) 2020 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group These authors contributed equally to this work. ABSTRACT A new benzophenone huanglongmycin (HLM) D (1) and two new monomeric xanthones huanglongmycin E (2) and F (3), together with four known aromatic polyketides aloesaponarin II (4) and the previously isolated huanglongmycin A-C (5–7) were obtained from cave-derived Streptomyces sp. CB09001. The structures of 1–3 were established based on 1D, 2D NMR and HRMS data. Compounds 1–7 may be biosynthesized by a type II huanglong- mycin polyketide synthase based on gene inactivation of hlmG encoding KSA in hlm gene cluster and their plausible biosynthetic mechanism was proposed. Structures of compounds 1–7.

topoisomerases (Liesenklas and Auterhoff 1966; Jinsart et al. 1992; Tosa et al. 1997; Kwok and Hurley 1998; Kasibhatla et al. 2005; Na 2009). Actinomycetes are also pro- ducers of polycyclic natural xanthones, such as albofungin, cervinomycin A2, simaomi- cin a and xantholipin (Gurevich et al. 1972; Nakagawa et al. 1987; Lee et al. 1989; Terui et al. 2003; Masters and Br€ase 2012). However, simple monomeric xanthones have been rarely isolated from actinomycetes (Winter et al. 2013). Caves are unique and under-explored niches to discover microorganisms cap- able to produce bioactive natural products (Ghosh et al. 2017). We recently identi- fied anthraquinone huanglongmycin (HLM) A (5) with moderate cytotoxicity lines, as well as syn-2, 3-diols and indole against multiple human cancer cell derivatives from a karstic cave-derived Streptomyces sp. CB09001 (Figure 1) (Jiang et al. 2018, 2019). In this study, we further isolate a new benzophenone huan- glongmycin D (1) and two new monomeric xanthone derivatives huanglongmycin E (2) and F (3) in a scaled-up fermentation using G1 culture medium, as well as aloesaponarin II (4) and the previously isolated huanglongmycin A-C (5–7). In con- trast to the previously reported monomeric xanthones, compounds 2 and 3 con- tain a new acetyl substitution in C-4 position of the xanthone scaffold. The biosynthetic origin of the isolated compounds was also proposed based on gene inactivation of two ketoacyl synthase genes in hlm type II polyketide synthase (PKS) biosynthetic gene cluster. 2. Results and discussion

Huanglongmycin D (1) was obtained as a light yellow solid. Its molecular formula was determined to be C18H14O9 on the basis of the positive-ion HR-ESI-MS data, with a [M þ H]þ ion peak observed at m/z 375.0720 (calculated for C18H15O9, 375.0716) (Supplementary material Figure S4). The 1H NMR spectrum of huanglongmycin D revealed three aromatic protons of AA’B spin system at H-40 (dH 7.23, 1H, t, J ¼ 8.0 Hz), H-30 and H-50 (dH 6.26, 2H, d, J ¼ 8.0 Hz), which suggested the presence of symmetrical trisubstituted benzene ring structure (Supplementary material Figure S5). The NMR res- onances for C-20 and C-60 (dC 161.9) were identical, which was consistent with a sym- metrically substituted aromatic ring with free hydroxy groups at C-20 and C-60 (Supplementary material Table S1). The assignment was supported by their 1H – 1H COSY correlations of H-30/H-40/H-50 and HMBC suggested the presence of a trisubsti- tuted benzene ring structure (Supplementary material Figures S7 and S10). Long range HMBC correlations from H-30/H-50 and H-2 to a signal at dC 200.4 (C-2a) suggested that compound 1 possesses a bicyclic benzophenone structure. The HMBC correlation between H-5a (dH 3.65) and C-4 (dC 129.5) was also observed. Therefore, compound 1 is similar to monodictyphenone isolated from many fungi species (Krick et al. 2007; Szwalbe et al. 2019). One difference was that the methyl group at dH 2.42 (3H, s, H-4b) is correlated to a carbonyl signal dC 203.6 (C-4a), suggestive of the presence of an ace- tyl substitute on the benzene structure. The observation of one downfield shifted

group at dH 2.42 (3H, s, H-4b) is correlated to a carbonyl signal dC 203.6 (C-4a), suggestive of the presence of an ace- tyl substitute on the benzene structure. The observation of one downfield shifted methylene group at dH 3.65 (2H, s, H-5a) in 1 and its HMBC correlation to signals at dC 172.1 (C-5b) and C-2 showed CH2-5a to reside close to C-2, with C-5a being connected to the carbonyl C-5b. Further analysis of the 1H NMR, 13C NMR and 2D NMR spectra of 1 confirmed the above assignment, which revealed that 1 is a benzophenone contain- ing tri- and pentasubstituted benzene rings (Figure 1 and Supplementary material Figures S5–S10).

Huanglongmycin E (2) was obtained as a brownish yellow solid. HR-ESI-MS data established the molecular formula of 2 as C17H12O6 (m/z 335.0530 [M þ Na]þ, calcu- lated for [M þ Na]þ ion at m/z 335.0532), indicating 12 degrees of unsaturation (Supplementary material Figure S4). The 1H NMR spectroscopic data of 2 revealed three aromatic protons at H-5 (dH 7.11, 1H, d, J ¼ 8.5 Hz), H-6 (dH 7.75, 1H, dd, J ¼ 8.5, 8.0 Hz), H-7 (dH 6.86, 1H, d, J ¼ 8.0 Hz), which can be grouped into one ABX spin sys- tem with the aid of the 1H-1H COSY correlations of H-5/H-6/H-7 (Supplementary mater- ial Figure S11). The aromatic proton at H-2 (dH 7.35, 1H, s) suggested the presence of pentasubstituted benzene ring structure. The 13C NMR spectrum of 2 displayed 17 car- bon signals, including three carbonyl carbons, twelve aromatic carbons, and two methyl carbons, which were further supported by DEPT and HSQC spectra of 2 (Supplementary material Figures S12, S14 and S15). The 1H NMR spectrum and 1H-1H COSY correlations of 2 resembled those of monodictyxanthone, except the resonances attributed to one acetyl group instead of an aromatic proton in monodictyxanthone (Krick et al. 2007) (Supplementary material Figure S13). This is supported by the HMBC correlations of H-14 to C-13 and C-4, as well as H-12 to C-1, C-2, C-3 and C-4 (Supplementary material Figure S16). Therefore, compound 2 was identified as a new acetyl substituted xanthone.

Huanglongmycin F (3) was also obtained as a brownish yellow solid. Its molecular formula C18H12O8, was established upon analysis of the HR-ESI-MS ion peak at m/z 357.0605 [M þ H]þ (calculated for [M þ H]þ ion at m/z 357.0605), which afforded 13 degrees of unsaturation and showed a mass difference of 44 mass units (CO2) with 2 (Supplementary material Figure S4). The similarity to compound 2 was obvious in all of the NMR data of 3, except the resonances at dH 3.84 (2H, s, H-12) and dC 38.2 (C- 12), as well as a carbonyl dC 171.2 (C-13), instead of a methyl group in 3 (Supplementary material Figures S17–S22). This difference between compounds 2 and 3 was attributed to the decarboxylation of compound 3. On that basis, compound 3 was also identified as a highly substituted xanthone. The isolation of two undescribed xanthone 2 and 3 of Streptomyces origin is interesting, since xanthones are mainly produced by plants, fungi and lichens (Vieira and Kijjoa 2005; El-Seedi et al. 2010; Wezeman et al. 2015). One putative hlm gene cluster was previously suggested to be responsible for the biosynthesis of huanglongmycins (Jiang et al. 2018). HlmG encoding KSa in the hlm gene cluster in S. sp. CB09001 wild-type strain was thus knocked-out by a single cross- over homologous recombination. The resulted DhlmG mutant YX1001 abolished the production of compounds 1–7 (Supplementary material Figure S2A). In contrast, gene inactivation of the KSa gene of an alternative type II PKS gene cluster in S. sp. CB09001 had no apparent effects on huanglongmycins production (Supplementary material Figure S2B).

Therefore, compounds 1–7 are likely biosynthesized by the huanglongmycin PKS, involving the minimal PKSs HlmGFE, the C-9 specific ketoreductase HlmD, cyclase HlmC and tailoring enzymes (Supplementary material Figure S29). The biosynthesis of compound 1, the precursor of xanthone 2 and 3, might involve a Baeyer-Villiger oxida- tion from SEK26, the anthraquinone from an engineered S. coelicolor CH999 strain (Hopwood 1997). The isolation of putative shunt metabolites 6 and 7 suggested the leakage of highly-reactive polyketide intermediates after the initial cyclisation of C-7/C- 12, while the formation of compound 4 may result from a 16-carbon polyketide inter- mediate (McDaniel et al. 1995; Zhou et al. 2010; Zhang et al. 2017; Huang et al. 2018; Jiang et al. 2018). 3.1. General materials and methods

Bacterial strains and plasmids used in this study are listed in Table S1 (Supplementary material). E. coli strains were cultured at 37 (cid:3)C in Luria–Bertani liquid/solid medium. Actinomycetes strains were inoculated in ISP-2 medium (4 g/L glucose, 4 g/L yeast extract, 10 g/L malt extract, 20 g/L agar, pH 7.0) or R2A medium (0.5 g/L glucose, 0.5 g/L soluble starch, 0.5 g/L yeast powder, 0.5 g/L peptone, 0.5 g/L acid hydrolysed casein, 0.3 g/L sodium pyruvate, 0.3 g/L K2HPO4, 0.024 g/L MgSO4(cid:4)7H2O, 20 g/L agar, pH ¼ 7.0) or G1 medium (20 g/L soluble starch, 0.5 g/L NaCl, 1 g/L KNO3, 0.5 g/L MgSO4(cid:4)7H2O, 0.01 g/L FeSO4(cid:4)7H2O, 0.5 g/L K2HPO4, 20 g/L agar, pH ¼ 7.0) for sporula- tion and tryptic soy broth (TSB) liquid medium for growth of mycelium and isolation of total DNA. ISP-4 (10 g/L soluble starch, 1 g/L tryptone, 0.5 g/L yeast powder, 1 g/L

NaCl, 1 g/L KNO3, 1 g/L MgSO4(cid:4)7H2O, 0.001 g/L FeSO4(cid:4)7H2O, 1 g/L K2HPO4, 2 g/L CaCO3, 2 g/L (NH4)2SO4, 20 g/L agar, pH 7.4) or G1 supplied with 10 mM MgCl2 was used for conjugation. The media were supplemented with appropriate antibiotics for selection: apramycin 50 lg/mL for Streptomyces; apramycin 50 lg/mL, kanamycin 50 lg/mL, ampicillin 100 lg/mL, chloramphenicol 25 lg/mL for E. coli. Oligonucleotide primer synthesis and DNA sequencing of PCR products were per- formed by Tsingke Biotech. Co., Changsha, China. Golden Star T6 Super PCR Mix (1.1(cid:5)) and T5 Super PCR Mix (2(cid:5)) were purchased from Tsingke. Restriction enzymes were purchased from New England Biolabs. T4 DNA ligase was purchased from Takara Biotech. Co., Beijing, China. SanPrep Column DNA Gel Extraction Kit and SanPrep Spin Column & Collection Tube (Plasmid) were purchased from Sangon Biotech. Co., Shanghai, China. GelStain was purchased from TransGen Biotech. Co., Changsha, China. All other chemicals and reagents were purchased from Sangon or Sinopharm Biotech. Co., Shanghai, China, unless specified.

HRESIMS spectra were recorded on an LTQ-ORBITRAP-ETD instrument. NMR spectra were acquired using a Brucker 400 MHz or 500 MHz spectrometer. Chemical shifts were reported in ppm relative to DMSO-d6 (d ¼ 2.50 ppm) for 1H NMR and DMSO-d6 (d ¼ 39.60 ppm) for 13C NMR spectroscopy. CD spectra were recorded on J-815 from JASCO. Column chromatography (CC) was carried out on silica gel (100–200 mesh and 300–400 mesh, Yantai Jiangyou Silica Gel, Yantai, China) and polyamide (100–200 mesh, Sinopharm). Semipreparative reversed phase-high-performance liquid chroma- tography (RP-HPLC) was performed using a Waters 1525 Binary HPLC Pump equipped with a Waters 2489 UV/Visible Detector and using a Welch Ultimate AQ-C18 column (250 (cid:5) 10 mm, 5 lm). The flow rate of semipreparative RP-C18 HPLC was 3 mL/min, and the mobile phase was CH3CN/H2O (containing 0.2% formic acid) with a linear gra- dient program in 20 min (5% to 95% for 15 min, followed by 95% for 2 min, and 95% to 5% for 0.5 min, followed by 5% for 2.5 min). 3.2. Recombinant plasmids construction and conjugation

The plasmids and primers (restriction sites were italicized) used in this study are listed in Table S1 and S2 (Supplementary material). Genomic DNA of the target strain was prepared according to the standard procedure. In order to inactivate the hlmG gene in the hlm gene cluster, a 1.2-kb DNA fragment internal to hlmG was amplified from the genomic DNA of CB09001, using the Golden Star T6 Super PCR Mix (1.1(cid:5)) (Tsingke). It was cloned into the sites of pOJ260 plasmid (Bierman et al. 1992) through HindIII and EcoRI sites via the T4 DNA ligase (Takara) to generate pXY1001, and confirmed by In order to inactivate the KSa gene in the alternative type II PKS DNA sequencing. gene cluster in CB09001, a DNA fragment internal to the KSa gene 3116 was similarly amplified by the same protocols above, and inserted into pOJ260 via HindIII and EcoRI sites to generate pXY1002. Then, pXY1001 and pXY1002 were individually introduced into CB09001 by conjugation. The resulting apramycin-sensitive exconjugants were verified by colony PCR using the T5 Super PCR Mix (2(cid:5)) and sequenced to obtain sin- gle-crossover mutants YX1001 and YX1002. 3.3. Fermentation and metabolites profile analysis The strains CB09001, YX1001 and YX1002 were fermented using G1 medium. In brief, these strains were grown in 250 mL flasks containing 50 mL of TSB medium and were incubated at 30 (cid:3)C on rotary shakers (230–250 rpm) for 36–48 h. Then 5 mL of seed cul- ture was transferred to 50 mL G1 production medium, with the addition of 3% (w/v) macroporous resin DA201-H (Jiangsu Su Qing Water Treatment Engineering Group, Jiangyin, China) in a 250 mL flask and cultured for 7 days at 30 (cid:3)C and 230–250 rpm.

After fermentation, the resins were collected and dried. Then they were extracted with MeOH and analysed on a waters High Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC) system equipped with a PDA detector, C18 column (2.7 lm, 4.6 (cid:5) 50 mm, Waters). The mobile phase consisted of buffer A (ultrapure H2O containing 0.1% HCOOH and 0.1% CH3CN) and buffer B (chromatographic grade CH3CN containing 0.1% HCOOH) was applied at a flow rate of 0.4 mL/min. A linear gradient program (60% buffer A and 40% buffer B to 50% buffer A and 50% buffer B for 2 min, 50% buf- fer A and 50% buffer B to 0% buffer A and 100% buffer B for 5 min, followed by 60% buffer A and 40% buffer B for 5 min) was used. 3.4. The scaled-up fermentation of S. sp. CB09001 and isolation of 1–7

In the scaled-up fermentation of S. sp. CB09001, the seed culture (50 mL) was aseptic- ally transferred to 2 L (cid:5) 12 Erlenmeyer flasks containing 500 mL G1 medium and fer- mented for 7 days. After fermentation, three batches of DA201-H resins (450, 450 and 150 g) were sequentially added into the culture supernatant and mixed by a pitch blade impeller at 100 rpm for 1–5 hours. The resins were filtered and extracted with ethanol (3 (cid:5) 2 L). The combined 6-L ethanol extract was subsequently evaporated in vacuo to afford the crude extract, which was subjected to silica gel CC using a succes- sive elution of petroleum ether (PE)/EtOAc and EtOAc/MeOH containing 1% formic acid. Fraction A3 (PE/EtOAc 90/10-80/20) was further purified by silica gel CC eluting with PE/EtOAc (90/10) to give three fractions. The first two fractions were subse- quently purified through silica gel CC and crystallisation, to yield the known com- pounds aloesaponarin II (4) (2.1 mg) and huanglongmycin A (5) (2.3 mg), respectively. Fraction A14 (EtOAc/MeOH 90/10-40/60) was subjected to silica gel and Sephadex LH- 20 CC, as well as semipreparative RP-HPLC, to yield huanglongmycin D (1) (2.1 mg), huanglongmycin E (2) (2.4 mg), huanglongmycin F (3) (1.3 mg) and the known com- pounds huanglongmycin B (6) (0.6 mg) and huanglongmycin C (7) (1.1 mg).

In conclusion, huanglongmycin D-E (1–3) were identified from a cave-derived Streptomyces species. The huanglongmycin type II PKS may be responsible for their biosynthesis. The biosynthetic mechanism for the formation of these xanthones and benzophenone would require future studies, including isotopic labelling, in vitro and in vivo characterisation of the hlm biosynthetic gene cluster. This study suggests that exploring cave Streptomyces may lead to the discovery of new natural products and biosynthetic insights into monomeric xanthone formation.
